&gt; Should a test case return a success or failure on a method when it throws an 
&gt; exception.


It depends what you want to test.

For example, the method loader.loadFile(String filename) loads your file.

Test 1: test if you can load a valid file:

public void testLoadSuccess() {
    try {
       loader.loadFile(&quot;correctFileName.txt&quot;);
    } catch (Exception e) {
       fail(&quot;NO expection should have been thrown&quot;);
    }
    // if you get here, everything was fine and because that&#39;s what
    // you wanted to test, just do nothing
}

Test 2: test that if you load an file that does not exist, the 
FileNotFoundException is thrown:

public void testLoadFNFEThrown() {
    try {
       loader.loadFile(&quot;INcorrectFileName.txt&quot;);
       // if you arrive there, then your loadFile method does not
       // work properly -&gt; simply tell that the test failed.
       fail(&quot;FNFE should have been thrown&quot;);
    } catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
       // in that case, everything&#39;s fine -&gt; just exit the method
       // this will count as a success because no AssertionFailedExc.
       // has been thrown
       return;
    } catch (Exception e) {
       fail(&quot;FNFE should have been thrown and not another exception&quot;);
    }
}

Repeat the Test 2 for every exception that can be thrown by a method.

You can also re-throw the exception but IMO you loose information (you 
don&#39;t know why the error appened, just that it happened).

